            <h1 id="heading-one">Havan: The Sacred Fire Ritual</h1>
            <img src="images/havan1.jpg" alt="Havan Image 1">
            <p>Havan, also known as Homam or Yajna, is a sacred fire ritual in Hinduism that involves making offerings
                into a consecrated fire. It is a powerful and ancient practice that has been performed for thousands of
                years.</p>
            <p>The primary purpose of havan is to create a spiritual atmosphere that is conducive to the worship of
                deities and the practice of meditation. The fire is considered a purifier and a symbol of the divine
                presence.</p>
            <p>During a havan ceremony, various materials such as ghee (clarified butter), grains, herbs, and wood are
                offered into the fire while chanting Vedic mantras. Each offering has a symbolic meaning and is believed
                to invoke specific blessings.</p>
            <p>Havan is often performed on special occasions such as weddings, housewarmings, and other important
                ceremonies. It is believed to bring prosperity, health, and spiritual upliftment to the participants.
            </p>
            <img src="images/havan2.jpg" alt="Havan Image 2">
